PRE-PUSH HOOK SETUP
===================

This hook runs unit and integration tests inside Docker before
allowing a push to feature branches of app teams
(e.g. weight/my-feature, billing/fix-bug, frontend/add-login).

It does NOT trigger on the app branches themselves (weight, billing,
frontend) — those are PR-protected and no one can push to them directly.

REQUIREMENTS:
  - Docker must be running on your machine
  - A .env file must exist in your app folder (copy from .env.example)
  - Tests must follow the exact folder structure below

TEST FOLDER STRUCTURE:
  The hook looks for tests in specific folder paths inside your
  app folder. These names are exact — any other naming will be
  silently skipped.

  <your-app-folder>/
  ├── tests/
  │   ├── unit/           <- unit tests go here
  │   └── integration/    <- integration tests go here

  Examples:
    weight/tests/unit/test_weight.py
    billing/tests/integration/test_api.py

  WRONG names (will be silently ignored):
    tests/unit_tests/     <- wrong
    tests/Units/          <- wrong
    test/unit/            <- wrong ("test" instead of "tests")
    unit_tests/           <- wrong (must be inside tests/)

  The hook runs pytest on these folders inside the Docker container.
  If a folder doesn't exist, the hook skips it and lets the push
  through — so make sure your tests are in the right place.

Step 1 - Get the hooks folder onto your branch (team lead does this once):

  This folder lives on the devops branch. To bring it into your
  team branch, run this from your branch. You don't need to switch
  branches — this command reaches into the devops branch on the
  remote and copies the hooks folder into your current branch.

  IMPORTANT: Run all commands from the repo root folder, NOT from
  inside your team's subfolder (e.g. weight/, billing/).
  To find your repo root: git rev-parse --show-toplevel

  git fetch origin devops
  git checkout origin/devops -- hooks
  git add hooks/
  git commit -m "Add pre-push hook"

  Then open a PR to merge this into your team branch (weight,
  billing, or frontend). You cannot push directly — the branch
  is protected.

Step 2 - Every developer on the team (one time each):

  git pull
  ./hooks/setup.sh

  This copies the hook into your local .git/hooks/ folder,
  which is where Git looks for hooks. Git never syncs this
  folder — that's why the copy is needed.

Step 3 - Make sure you have a .env file:

  The Docker containers need database credentials and other
  settings to start. These are stored in a .env file inside
  your app folder (e.g. weight/.env, billing/.env).

  This file is NOT tracked by Git (it's in .gitignore) so you
  won't get it from git pull. You create it yourself from the
  template:

  cd <your-app-folder>
  cp .env.example .env

  Then open .env and fill in the values (database name, password, etc).
  Ask your team lead if you're not sure what to put.

  The hook will refuse to run without this file.

Done. The hook runs automatically on every push from now on.

What it does:
  - Push to a feature branch (e.g. weight/my-feature) →
    Docker containers spin up, tests run, containers tear down
  - Tests pass → push goes through
  - Tests fail → push is blocked, fix locally and try again
  - Push to any other branch → hook does nothing

To skip the hook once (not recommended):
  git push --no-verify

TO REMOVE THE HOOK COMPLETELY:

  For a single developer — removes it from your machine only:

    rm .git/hooks/pre-push

  For the whole team — team lead does this:

    1. Go to the repo root folder
    2. git rm -r hooks/
    3. git commit -m "Remove pre-push hook"
    4. Open a PR to your team branch and merge it
    5. Tell every developer on your team to run:
       rm .git/hooks/pre-push

  Step 5 is required because deleting the folder from the branch
  does NOT remove the hook from each developer's machine.
  The hook lives in .git/hooks/ which Git never syncs.
